      "source": [
        "The needed investment doesn't seem so large, around 5% of the global GDP, if one compares it to the *per year* Global Gross Domestic Product (GDP) estimated at around 100 Trillion USD in 2022 and growing to 105 Trillion USD in 2023 [@aarononeillGlobalGDP198520282023; @imfWorldEconomicOutlook2023GDPgrowth]. In essence, the estimated total investment gap in climate fits into the economic growth of 1-2 years of the global economy. [@oecdOECDEconomicOutlook2024] projects steady economic growth 3.1% in 2024 and 3.2% in 2025 while the [@worldbankGlobalEconomicProspects2024] is more conservative projecting 2.6% and 2.7% respectively.\n",
        "\n",
        "The lack of funding in green energy especially affects emerging economies [@MobilizingCapitalEmerging2022]. *\"We can and must channel private capital into nature-based solutions. This will require policy and regulatory support, catalytic capital and financial innovation\"* argued the CEO Green Finance Institute, Dr Rhian-Mari Thomas, ahead of COP27 in Egypt [@GreenFinanceInstitute2023]. It's not happening fast enough."
